<HL>
   Jet Makes Maiden Flight
   In Air Force Job Rivalry
</HL>
<DATE>
08/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   NOC MD UTX LK BA GD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. -- A version of the Air
Force's next-generation fighter jet, built by Northrop Corp.
and McDonnell Douglas Corp., took to the skies for the first
time yesterday, setting the stage for a showdown with another
version of the aircraft built by a rival team of aerospace
companies.
   The twin-engine YF-23, with a Northrop test pilot, Paul
Metz, at the controls, climbed to 25,000 feet, and functional
checks of basic subsystems were performed during the
early-morning, 50-minute flight. United Technologies Corp.'s
Pratt &amp; Whitney division made the engines on the YF-23.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The airplane flies very clean, much cleaner than we
expected," <PERSON>Mr. Metz</PERSON> said. "During the climb-out, I was using
considerably less power than I expected, and the chase
airplanes were on afterburners just to stay with me -- with
my landing gear down."
   The other team, composed of <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Boeing Co.</ORGANIZATION> and
<ORGANIZATION>General Dynamics Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, is scheduled to roll out its Advanced
Tactical Fighter, the YF-22, tomorrow at a <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed</ORGANIZATION> site in
<LOCATION>Palmdale</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>. The first flight of that plane is expected
to be next month.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>, which wants 750 of the jets to replace the
aging F-15 fighter, is scheduled to choose the winning team
in <DATE>April</DATE> and award the full-scale development contract three
months later. A second YF-23, which was delivered to a test
facility here in <DATE>June</DATE>, will fly with <ORGANIZATION>General Electric Co.</ORGANIZATION>
engines.
</TEXT>
