<HEAD>Boeing Allows a Look at Secret Unmanned Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Boeing Co.</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> released a photo of a
secret unmanned airplane it said made its first flight <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> released few details about the experimental aircraft,
other than to say it successfully completed its first flight and
would undergo further flight tests ``to characterize the
capabilities of this type of vehicle.''
   The airplane has a long, skinny fuselage with narrow, flexible
wings. It is powered by two propeller-driven engines, described by
the trade publication <ORGANIZATION>Aviation Week and Space Technology</ORGANIZATION> as
<ORGANIZATION>Teledyne Continental</ORGANIZATION> liquid-cooled piston engines.
   In <DATE>April 1986</DATE>, a similar plane was photographed outside a hanger
at the <LOCATION>Grant County Airport</LOCATION> in <PERSON>Moses Lake</PERSON>, in central <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
<ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> declined to comment on that aircraft.
   <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION>Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency</ORGANIZATION> had
expressed interest in the aircraft and has provided some money to
participate in flight evaluation. The agency has classified certain
aspects of the aircraft design and performance, <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The plane resembles <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION>'s Compass Cope remotely piloted
vehicle, an unmanned aircraft powered by a single jet engine.
<ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> built two of the planes for the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>.
   The Compass Cope was 40 feet long with a 90-foot wingspan. It
made its first flight at <ORGANIZATION>Edwards Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> in
<DATE>July 1973</DATE>.
</TEXT>
