<HEAD>Field Where Wrights Learned To Fly Dedicated as Historic Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The meadow where <PERSON>Orville</PERSON> and <PERSON>Wilbur Wright</PERSON>
learned to turn and maneuver the world's first airplanes has been
dedicated as a national historic landmark.
   With a replica of one of <PERSON>Wright</PERSON> brothers' planes buzzing
overhead, about 400 military and civilian dignitaries attended the
dedication ceremony <DATE>Friday</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>Huffman Prairie Flying Field on
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION>.
   The <PERSON>Wright</PERSON> brothers first flew at <LOCATION>Kitty Hawk</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>, on <DATE>Dec. 17,
1903</DATE>. They then returned to <LOCATION>Dayton</LOCATION> and learned to maneuver the
aircraft at <ORGANIZATION>Huffman Prairie</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``They spent almost the whole year learning how to turn it and
control it,'' said base historian <PERSON>Lois Walker</PERSON>. ``The very first
circle in powered flight history was made on <DATE>Sept. 20, 1904</DATE>.''
   The 84-acre field was designated an historic landmark last <DATE>July</DATE>.
</TEXT>
