<HEAD>Second Prototype of Advanced Tactical Fighter Rolls Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed Corp.</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> unveiled its
version of a futuristic fighter proposed for the <DATE>21st century</DATE>, as
<ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> officials cited the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> crisis as the need for
such a craft.
   The Lockheed YF-22 prototype of the <ORGANIZATION>Advanced Tactical Fighter</ORGANIZATION>
followed <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s launch of a prototype made by <ORGANIZATION>Northrop Corp</ORGANIZATION>. The
two designs are competing for a multibillion-dollar contract.
   The plane <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed</ORGANIZATION> unveiled at its <LOCATION>Palmdale</LOCATION> manufacturing plant
was much more compact than the <ORGANIZATION>Northrop</ORGANIZATION> version.
   Both planes have smooth contours to help them evade radar and
are built of advanced composite materials. The <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed</ORGANIZATION> aircraft
has stubby wings, while the <ORGANIZATION>Northrop</ORGANIZATION> plane is longer, with a
cigar-like fuselage and a wingspan that looks like a kite.
   A music system blared <PERSON>Wagner</PERSON>'s ``Flight of the Valkyries'' as
the <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed</ORGANIZATION> plane was rolled out, although unlike its competition,
the YF-22 stayed on the ground after its rollout. Officials would
not say when it would be flown.
   Lockheed chairman <PERSON>Daniel M. Tellep</PERSON> said it will not matter that
<ORGANIZATION>Northrop</ORGANIZATION> got its aircraft up first.
   ``It is not he who flies first, it is he who flies best,'' he
said.
   The contract calls for 750 fighter planes for the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> and
approximately 500 for the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> at a cost of <MONEY>$51 million</MONEY> apiece. The
price tag is about twice the cost of the F-15 Eagle, the current
front-line fighter deployed in the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>ATF</ORGANIZATION> program faced fading prospects for approval in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>
before <LOCATION>Iraq</LOCATION>'s invasion of <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION> on <DATE>Aug. 2</DATE>, but the crisis has
enhanced prospects for approval of major defense projects.
   <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON>Joseph W. Ralston</PERSON> said he is optimistic
about congessional funding for the <ORGANIZATION>ATF</ORGANIZATION> program desspite recent
defense spending cuts.
   In building the YF-22 prototype, <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed</ORGANIZATION> teamed with the <ORGANIZATION>Boeing
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>General Dynamics Corp</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Northrop</ORGANIZATION> teamed with <ORGANIZATION>McDonnell
Douglas Corp.</ORGANIZATION> for its test version of the futuristic fighter.
   The winner must give the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION> a fighter plane that can fly
twice the speed of sound, is highly maneuverable and uses
radar-evading stealth technology.
   If <ORGANIZATION>Northrop</ORGANIZATION> gets the contract, <ORGANIZATION>ATF</ORGANIZATION> planes will be built in
<LOCATION>Southern California</LOCATION>. Lockheed has said if it wins the competition,
the fighters will be made in <LOCATION>Marietta</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ga</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
